{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17533653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17533653"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:37:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:37:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14855"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14855","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14855"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.86,0.03,0.02,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7546"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90491"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7546"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14855"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74738"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2705"},{"type":"tags","id":"3231"},{"type":"tags","id":"4939"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5185"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18464"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25045"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90491","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90491"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with her daughter who is concerned about abnormal movements that have developed insidiously over the past year. She has a history of bipolar disorder treated with haloperidol for 20 years, and type 2 diabetes mellitus. Her medications include haloperidol, metformin, and vitamin D supplements. She lives independently but her daughter visits regularly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are repetitive, stereotyped movements of her mouth including lip-smacking and tongue protrusion. These movements temporarily decrease when she touches her chin (sensory trick) or when performing voluntary actions like drinking water. The movements worsen with emotional stress and improve during sleep. There is also mild postural tremor of the hands, intermittent cervical extension that improves with gentle posterior pressure on the forehead, and subtle choreiform movements of the fingers. Recent thyroid function tests, serum copper, ceruloplasmin, and brain MRI are normal. There is no family history of movement disorders.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely primary diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Huntington disease","Tardive dyskinesia","Adult-onset primary dystonia","Neuroacanthocytosis","Chorea-acanthocytosis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a complex movement disorder featuring overlapping phenomenology including stereotyped orofacial movements, dystonic posturing, and subtle choreiform movements. The presence of sensory tricks (geste antagoniste) and action-specific improvement could suggest primary dystonia, but several features point towards tardive dyskinesia as the primary diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETardive dyskinesia\u003C/strong\u003E can present as part of a broader tardive syndrome that includes elements of dystonia, stereotypy, and chorea. The temporal relationship with long-term antipsychotic use, characteristic orofacial involvement, and improvement with voluntary actions are typical features. While sensory tricks are classically associated with primary dystonia, they can also occur in tardive syndromes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdult-onset primary dystonia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with focal dystonia that may spread to contiguous regions. While the presence of sensory tricks and action-specific improvement would support this diagnosis, the combination with stereotyped movements and chorea, plus the relationship to antipsychotic use, makes this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHuntington disease\u003C/strong\u003E can present with a combination of chorea, dystonia, and psychiatric symptoms. However, the normal brain MRI, absence of cognitive decline, lack of family history, and predominance of stereotyped rather than random movements make this unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeuroacanthocytosis\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Echorea-acanthocytosis\u003C/strong\u003E are rare neurodegenerative conditions that can present with mixed movement disorders including chorea, dystonia, and stereotypies. They typically present at a younger age and are associated with peripheral neuropathy, seizures, and cognitive decline. The absence of self-mutilating lip and tongue biting, normal brain MRI, and late age of onset make these diagnoses unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mixed movement disorders with overlapping phenomenology require careful observation of temporal patterns and modifying factors to determine the primary diagnosis.","Tardive syndromes can present with complex phenomenology including elements of dyskinesia, dystonia, stereotypy, and tremor.","The presence of sensory tricks (geste antagoniste) does not exclude tardive dyskinesia as they can occur in both primary dystonia and tardive syndromes."],"references":["D\u0027Souza RS, Aslam SP, Hooten WM. Extrapyramidal Side Effects. [Updated 2025 Jan 19]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534115/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74738"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14855"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74738"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T08:58:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T08:59:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7546"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90491"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links"